how violence was experienced, represented, justified, or contested. His innovative analysis reveals how various groups employed the language of religious violence to construct their own identities, to undermine the legitimacy of their rivals, and to advance themselves in the competitive and high-stakes process of Christianizing the Roman Empire.Gaddis pursues case studies and themes including martyrdom and persecution, the Donatist controversy and other sectarian conflicts, zealous monks' assaults on pagan temples, the tyrannical behavior of powerful bishops, and the intrigues of church councils. In addition to illuminating a core issue of late antiquity, this book also sheds light on thematic and comparative dimensions of religious violence in other times, including our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianity and culturexHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aChurch historyy4th century. 0aChurch historyy5th century. 0aMartyrdomxChristianity. 0aMartyrdom. 0aPersecutionxHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aPersecution. 0aViolencexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aViolencexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aancient history.  aancient rome.  aancient world.  aantiquity.  aarchaeology.  abishop.  achristian roman empire.  achristian sects.  achristianity.  achurch councils.  acloister.  aconversion.  acrusade.  adonatist controversy.  aearly church.  aempire.  aholy war.  aimperialism.  ainquisition.  alaw.  amartyr.  amassacres.  amissionary.  amonks.  anonfiction.  apagan temples.  apagans.  aparrhesia.  apersecution.  areligion.  areligious conflict.  areligious extremism.  areligious violence.  areligious war.  asaint.  atemples.  aviolence.  azealots.08iTitle is part of eBook package: